snippet.textDisplay:
Approximately 45% of child mortalities (children under 5 years old) are related to hunger; 5.3 million children (again, under 5) died in 2018.

0.45 * 5.3 million = ~2.4 million

average (mean) deaths per day:
2 400 000 / 365 = ~6500 deaths/day

So, approximately 6500 children under the age of 5 die a day. I open YouTube for a quick break from studying, wonder what's on trending, see this hot garbage, and think: what gives us, comparatively entitled people, the right to sit and watch wealthy people waste money on things they don't need when people, children included, are starving, undereducated, and have limited access to health care? Are we not obligated to actually help or do we just pretend these issues don't exist? People who are smart or fortunate enough to make MORE money than they need should be given grief for not helping those who ARE in need.

Sources:

https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/malnutrition

https://www.who.int/gho/child_health/mortality/mortality_under_five_text/en/
